  Book Recommendations

I've learned the creative process is a very delicate journey that requires emotional resistance. A few art books have greatly impacted my work as an artist and I believe they will help you too. I have referenced each one of these books during my conversations with others about Artificial intelligence and I believe we have a lot to learn from their insights. If you are a reader, I can't recommend them enough.

The Artists' Way

Warning: Proceed with caution... I quit my job after reading The Artists Way.

The Artists' Way is a 12-week journey into the deep realms of artistic expression, acting as a spiritual guide that unearths the hidden creative prowess within us, even when marred by self-doubt and societal norms. Its key message: creativity is not a scarce resource, but a divine channel, constantly accessible to those willing to take the plunge.

The War of Art

The War of Art employs the metaphor of a war zone to embody the internal conflicts that artists often face, imbuing us with strategies to conquer our personal demons of procrastination, fear, and self-doubt. Its core proposition: the most formidable enemy of creativity lies within, but it's a war that can be won with perseverance.

Key Takeaway: Everything can be resistance to you creating your art.

Steal Like an Artist

Steal Like an Artist is a provocative assertion that originality is overrated, and creativity is often a product of intuitive borrowing, remixing, and personal interpretation of the works that inspire us. Its bold declaration: true artistry isn't about pulling ideas out of thin air, but rather about cleverly 'stealing' and combining existing ideas to produce something uniquely yours.

Key Takeaways: We all draw from unconscious inspiration sources. Mash ideas together to create new pieces of art. Originality is a myth.

Creativity, Inc.

Creativity, Inc. offers a view into the culture of Pixar and its innovative approaches to fostering creativity, advocating that a nourishing environment plays a critical role in bringing creative ideas to life.

Key Takeaway: Iterate to perfection. Just get a bad first draft out there and stop overthinking it.
